DATA ANALYSIS

Preliminary Findings

Decreasing under-five Mortality Rate is an endeavor that requires persistence. Efforts and expenditure in previous years compound each year so that the net effect is a year over year decrease. As such, one would not expect a tight correlation between year over year expenditure and year over year under-five Mortality Rate. For example, a large increase or decrease in expenditure in a given year may not have an immediately identifiable impact on mortality rate in that year.

A more suitable analysis may be to use annual moving averages for the health expenditure and comparison to a baseline year for the under-five Mortality Rate. This would better capture the nature of a cumulative effort.

This being said, there are still some notable observations that can be made:

  • In general, under-five Mortality Rate decreases year over year across all regions.

  • The only region with an increase in under-five Mortality Rate is Latin America and Caribbean, which had a 32% decrease in health expense in 2016 compared with 2014, the largest percentage decrease in health expense across all regions and all years.

Future Work and Improvements

  • Deeper breakdown of health expenses at the country level.
  • Analysis of additional factors that can affect under-five Mortality Rate (i.e.war, novel viruses, natural disasters, GDP, etc).
  • Using an analysis that examines spending efficiency, it is possible to build a forecasting model in order to monitor the progress for each country or region and estimate the amount of spending needed in order to meet the 2030 SDG targets.
